It should be around 3450 now according to a different source with daily updates, so 3000-3800 should be the most probable. The average being 3450 instead of 3400 should favor the 3400-3800 range, but the current trend is downward. I'm not sure which of these effects is stronger, so I'm putting them both at 39%. The variability rarely exceed 300-400 in two weeks time, so a ~80% confidence interval for this range seems right. I'm not going higher because both my knowledge of gas prices and forecasting in general is very limited, so there's a non-significant chance of unknown unkowns that could throw off my perceived accuracy.

Very tough. Just glancing at the EIA data, we're at a pretty high spot for gas. The last prolonged period of oil uncertainty occurred around 2011 and extended until OPEC tried to flood the markets in late 2014 / 2015 to flush out US horizontal drillers. Historically, it appears that prices often remain elevated for years following an initial surge from one price range to another. I don't see why this would be any different. Oil prices have a somewhat negative correlation with the yield curve. There is downward pressure on the yield curve and another IR hike in May could push it closer to inversion. That could be seen as a bullish signal for oil. Further, interest rates could strengthen the dollar, making petrodollars more expensive. Ukraine / Russia could cause further dislocations in the supply market, but to-date it looks unlikely for any further pricing dislocations as India and the undeveloped world are still taking Russia oil. US supply will not be able to add meaningful barrels to the market by December, as even a large uptick in drilling rigs will not lead to significant increased production until at least next year. I weigh that against the fragility of the current US economy where asset inflation over the past 10 years, particularly in housing and predicated on sustained low Interest rates, makes us and much of the developed world more at shock to even a 1% IR hike. OPEC seems reluctant or unable to increase supply and Russia will not likely see material growth in production minus a resolution to the war that the West deems reasonable. It seems that most of the evidence points to sustained to increased prices at the pumps, with the risk to that being what I perceive to be a weak macro footing of the US and other economies in the developed world.
